Name: Atkins, Ariel
Caption:
#sayhername_Atatiana Jefferson and her eight-year-old nephew were playing video games in her Fort Worth home in the early morning of October 11th. A twenty-eight-year-old pre-med graduate, Jefferson went to the window of her bedroom to investigate noises coming from outside the house. Her decision — made in what should have been the security of her own home—would be her last. Outside her window was a man, wearing blue, empowered to take her life on the grounds that he felt threatened by a shadow in the window. 
 
Minutes earlier, her neighbor James Smith had noticed that the front door of Jefferson’s house was open. On an otherwise placid Saturday night, Smith was concerned about the safety of the Jefferson household so he decided to call the non-emergency line of his local police station to request a wellness check: “[There was no] domestic violence, no arguing, nothing that they should have been concerned about as far as them coming with guns drawn to my neighbor’s house,” said Smith. 
 
The Fort Worth police that arrived on-scene concealed their presence and entered Jefferson’s property without warning, as if they were investigating a crime-in-progress. 
 
The officer shouted, “Put your hands up! Show me your hands!” Almost immediately, he fired a single shot into Jefferson’s window. The video cuts. Minutes later, Atatiana Jefferson was pronounced dead. We will not forget. 
 
#sayhername_#atatianajefferson_#gameday_#happybirthdaytome

On June 18th 2017, Charleena Lyles, a pregnant mother of four, was killed by the police in her home, in Seattle, WA. Three of Charleena’s children were home when the shooting occurred. SHE had called the Seattle Police Department to report a burglary. The police officers knew that Charleena suffered from mental health issues and knew that she was a survivor of domestic violence and yet they did nothing to de-escalate the situation when they claimed Charleena brandished a knife. Charleena was a petite woman and her family has argued that the officers should have been able to subdue her with less than deadly force._#charleenalyles_#sayhername_#gameday

Name: Atkins, Ariel
Caption:
#sayhername 
On February 12, 2013, police were called to Kayla’s Shattuck Avenue apartment by a friend who was concerned about her mental health. Police arrived and immediately attempted to place her under arrest. Kayla was an African American, transgender woman living with schizophrenia. When officers wrestled her face down onto a futon on the floor, they should have known that this could impair her breathing. Up to six cops, using their full weight continued to restrain the panicked woman and even called for a “spit hood” to be placed on her head. Ultimately, they didn’t get a chance use it. They thought she had calmed down; in fact, she had stopped breathing._#kaylamoore_#transblacklivesmattertoo_#sayhername_#gameday

Name: Atkins, Ariel
Caption: #sayhername_On February 21, 2016 California police officers shot and killed 31-year-old Kisha Michael and her friend Marquintan Sandlin, 32, after initially finding them unconscious and sitting in a stopped car on Manchester Boulevard. Michael was shot 13 times and pronounced dead at the scene, while Sandlin, the driver, was shot eight times and pronounced dead a short time later at a nearby hospital. An autopsy recovered projectiles from at least two and as many as three different types of firearms–a shotgun, handgun and possibly a rifle–from Michael’s body. Grimes says witnesses reported that police fired as many as 100 shots at the pair in the car.

Name: Atkins, Ariel
Caption: #sayhername_On May 16, 2003, 57 year old Alberta Spruill was getting ready for work when New York police officers performed a “no knock” raid at her home. Officers broke down her door and launched a concussion grenade into her home. After handcuffing Spruill, officers realized that they were in the wrong place and had been misinformed about guns and drugs being in the apartment. Less than two hours later, Spruill passed away from a heart attack. No charges were ever filed._#albertaspruill_#sayhername_#gameday

Caption: Proud to be a part of the launch of_@Phenomenal_Media by publishing this op-ed with_@nnemkadi_. In this time of reckoning, we as WNBA players are making sports history by dedicating our 2020 season to social justice: declaring that Black Lives Matter, wearing Breonna Taylor's name on our jerseys, and showing up for the forgotten victims of police brutality and racial violence. That's why, more than ever before, we need you to show up for us because supporting WNBA players means more than just being a fan. Supporting us is feminism in action. Read our op-Ed on_@phenomenal_now

Name: Bradford, Crystal
Caption:
My key to success is letting go. I use to be so insecure about my body. . I use to be scared to show my legs. Yesterday at the Dead Sea a random insecurity came back lol i said wait a minute let me go ahead and put my shorts on and NOT show my legs man but nope , I’ve worked on them for years. So here they are. Lol
Sometimes i dance and i tell myself wait a minute nobody else is dancing. Being an influencer you will always be a step ahead. Often times people are not doing what you are doing. Now, I have nothing deep to say other than i give god the glory everyday that I’m not where i use to be. My mindset is constantly evolving. . . I’m gaining more and more angels I’m gaining more grace I’m gaining a better relationship with things that matter the most and i had to cut a lot of things and people off to get here. Toast to the good life __ .. long live Ricky @princerick__ long live my sis @mstaylorxo ! And hey z ! we miss your energy down here @zurlontipton37 #dauntewright #georgefloyd #dmx and so many more. #deadsea #float #itsaltwater

Name: Burdick, Cierra
Caption: A month ago, I flew straight from Poland to Phoenix to embark on another WNBA journey. I went into camp with no expectations, but no limitations either. My only goal was to learn as much as possible and enjoy playing along side some of the greatest to ever do it. A younger Cierra would have lost sleep to nerves and anxiety. More seasoned Cierra was just focused on having fun and competing. This league is the most competitive league in the world. Every single opportunity is a blessing not to be wasted. I’m grateful for all parts of the journey. I’m just having fun! #wnba #HaveFunPlayHard #letgoletgod

Name: Cambage, Liz
Caption:
a blessing and a honor ____ 
thank you_@playboy_for this feature. this one goes out to anyone who isn’t empowered or confident in their own skin and sexuality. I spent so many years as a teenager hating myself, trying to shrink myself in to someone I’m not. I really do hope my self love can help inspire those struggling to love their reflection, because I promise you, you are beautiful and lovable just the way you are!!! also thank you too the amazing team for making me feel so comfortable and loved on set. I was so nervous the day of the shoot, but the whole day I felt like I was shooting with my best friends ____ to read the article; LINK IN BIO __

I was so nervous the day of the shoot, but the whole day I felt like I was shooting with my best friends ____ to read the article; LINK IN BIO __

Name: Clarendon, Layshia
Caption: Link in bio! Blown away at @britnidlc phenomenal story telling skills. It’s one thing to have your story told and another to have it done by someone with such care, nuance and flat out skill. This is why we need people in positions who represent the communities they’re actually reporting on. Britni is a non binary writer who, in our conversations expanded my language and understanding around marginalized gender identities. It’s important to go beyond pointing out the obvious sports binary and how currently bodies are policed to squeeze people into rigid constructions of gender. How dope would it be if we started to have intentional conversations around how to create healthier, safer, more inclusive environments in sports for those of us who don’t fit the mold? Seems simple enough to me. That is unless people want us to shut up and not exist __. __ :@ruffdraft

Name: Cloud, Natasha
Caption:
This has been the first time in our careers that I’ve truly had an opportunity to sit back and just admire you. I am so incredibly proud of your growth not only as a player, but more so as the phenomenal person you are. This league has given you an immense amount of opportunity to not only showcase your talent, but more so your heart. You and all the other amazing women you’re surrounded by are pioneers for putting softball back on the map (where it should be). 
- 
You never cease to amaze me; and in that I think of all the young black and brown girls that will look at you in the same light. Representation for not only women, but for the young minority girls who will dream to be the next Lele Ocasio, the same as you dreamed to be the next_@natashawatley29_. I love you the mostest and can’t wait for what the future holds for you and this sport______#BetOnWomen_#SoftballWife_#DatJustMyBabyMama

Name: Dantas, Damiris
Caption: Muito surpresa e feliz em ser nomeada para lista Forbes Under 30, categoria Esportes @forbesbr . Esse destaque para mim, significa mais do que um reconhecimento pessoal, mas um reconhecimento da importância da luta, tanto para o desenvolvimento do basquete feminino, quanto contra as desigualdades sociais, especialmente de raça e gênero. 2020 foi um ano duro para todos nós, mas espero que a gente carregue muitos aprendizados para fazer 2021 diferente. Grande beijo! Feliz Ano Novo!

Name: Dantas, Damiris
Caption: ______ 9 anos desde a mais importante conquista na minha carreira. Essa medalha de bronze no mundial_@fiba_Sub19 abriu os caminhos pra mim e me fez acreditar que era possível me tornar uma jogadora de basquete profissional. O mundo me viu, foi lindo! __ Muito obrigada tia jane_@janetharcain_e_@institutojaneth_por acreditar desde o início. Hoje estou representando o Brasil na WNBA e é como um sonho de verdade! Por isso, faço questão de sempre ressaltar a EXTREMA importância do trabalho com as nossas meninas de base! E pra vocês aí, meninas que sonham em um dia se tornarem profissionais, ACREDITEM e contem com meu apoio. Quero acompanhar vocês, por favor, dê um oi aqui no comentários que já vou começar a te seguir! Estamos juntas!_#DD12_@basquetecbb_@nikebasketball_#BasqueteFeminino

Name: Dantas, Damiris
Caption: Muito orgulho em representar cada vez melhor as mulheres negras no esporte e também servir de exemplo para cada uma das meninas que sonham em se tornar uma jogadora de basquete feminino. Sei que não estou aqui sozinha e o apoio de vocês é tudo pra mim. É o que me dá forças pra entrar em quadra todos os dias. Amei essa entrevista que dei para o UOL Esportes, retratando um dos momentos mais importantes em minha carreira. Ainda temos muito trabalho pela frente, mas o importante é estamos todas juntas e de cabeça erguida. Link na Bio! __________#BasqueteFeminino_#BlackLivesMatter_#PoderParaOPovoPreto_@basquetecbb_@lbf.oficial_@nikebasketball

Name: Delle Donne, Elena
Caption: Poverty is a punishment in so many more ways that I realized. I was shocked to learn 1 in 3 parents worry they won’t have enough money to afford period products for their daughters. No period products means no school and no sports. Both are so important, and create essential and positive opportunities for young women. Being a girl and having a period should never be a reason not to play. Ever. Join the_#SupportedAlways_Instagram Live sessions happening every Wednesday from August 12 – September 30, 2020 to help girls continue to stay involved (even if virtually) in the activities they love. For everyone who joins a session,_@always_brand_will donate a month’s supply of period products, up to a half a million products, via_@womenssportsfoundation_, which is helping girls stay active all over the country and help_#endperiodpoverty.

Please listen wherever you get your podcasts, and let me know what you think!

Name: Lavender, Jantel
Caption: FBF-August 14,2019 I had my first surgery, and June 15, 2020 was the second. Today is the one year anniversary and I’m still on this scooter. Am I bitter? No!!!! I am grateful. Grateful for all the opportunities I have had because of this and all the people I have been able to connect with. It’s truly a blessing. And more importantly this moment in time, is BIGGER than ME! And I don’t question Gods timing! Thank you to everyone that checks on me on a daily and makes sure I’m good because it was hard!!!!! But when you reflect and you see the bigger picture you realize things are happening FOR you, not TO you! Life is GOOD! #sayhername #positivevibes #keepgoing #stayencouraged

Name: McCall, Erica
Caption:
Finally have some time to reflect on my amazing overseas season. Finished out not my 1st, 2nd, 3rd but 4th year with my Szekszárd sisters and it seems like each year gets better. It was season far from ideal for me personally, dealing with Covid and 2 serious injuries but God always reminds me everything works out for the better. Oh and even got to play with my sister for the first time ever. A true dream come true _

This team made some serious history and I am forever proud to call them family #csalad __

Name: McCoughtry, Angel
Caption:
During the last game, I had an accident on the court. Eerily similar to what happened the first time, and my results came back as a torn ACL , torn meniscus.  I was heartbroken. Again.

Initially, every negative thought came to my head.  Then I realized ..this game has been such a blessing to me and so has God. I will conquer this challenge even better than last time. I will recover and fight my way back to the court.
I still have tons of basketball to play, God has ALWAYS delivered for me .... and it’s not over yet! ________

Thank you to my Amazing teammates and the @lvaces organization for being so supportive. Let’s Go Aces!!
________________________

__ @mynamemister

Caption: Proud to be a part of the launch of_@Phenomenal_Media by publishing this op-ed with Sue. In this time of reckoning, we as WNBA players are making sports history by dedicating our 2020 season to social justice: declaring that Black Lives Matter, wearing Breonna Taylor's name on our jerseys, and showing up for the forgotten victims of police brutality and racial violence. Name: Parker, Candace
Caption: I’m thrilled to announce I’m partnering with_@CapitalOneCafe. This partnership is about so much more than finance and banking, it’s about life. And let me tell you…between moving back home to the Chicagoland area, balancing Lailaa being part-time at-home-school and part-time in-person school, and everything this past year has thrown into our lives, life is crazy. But I know I’m not the only one. We’re all going through something and I know how scary life can sometimes be, but it’s important that we talk about it._ So that’s exactly what I’m going to be doing with Capital One Café. We created a new online experience – featuring yours truly – and we’ll be talking about everything from our values, to relationships, to creating balance and how it all intersects with money._@CapitalOne_is reimagining banking by truly helping people, fostering well-being, and supporting across so many facets. Stay on the lookout for more!_#CapitalOnePartner_#ThisIsMyBlend_#CapitalOneCafe

Name: Robinson, Danielle
Caption:
My baby passed her board certification exam! I am so beyond proud of her y’all don’t even understand!! She studied for this exam for a YEAR straight! Mother Nature almost didn’t want her to be great when the snowpocalypse hit but even through that she studied in the dark(swipe left to see)! Her perseverance, persistence, and straight up will for me while working TWO full time jobs(by choice to help people) is unmatched. She truly is the hardest working woman I know!

Keep adding those letters behind your name babe ____

It’s the percentile for me __

I’m oh so proud of you soon to be Dr. Andrea Robinson ______

Name: Robinson, Danielle
Caption:
To my beautiful wife to be __

One year ago I asked you to spend forever with me and one year ago you said YES! With all of our people there I couldn’t have asked for a more magical night _

@dming24 you are my person and you have been for so many years. I thank God our paths continued to cross over and over and over again until they eventually united as one. You truly are my better half. I learn daily from you and am inspired by you even more than you know. My heart is truly yours and only yours until the end of time. As you say “you’re stuck with me” __

Even though 2020 hasn’t been the year anyone has anticipated, there is hope and promise in knowing that we are one year closer to forever. I love you with all of me and just know that I ALWAYS got you! __

I love you. I love you. I love you. And I can’t wait to marry you ____

Name: Robinson, Danielle

Name: Sykes, Brittney
Caption:
I’ll never forget finding out after a game I was called the worse defender on my team ... by that time in the season ... I had already lost my love for the game and felt alone.... fast forward to Year 4 , New Team , New Opportunity ... and one hell of a chip on my shoulder. I took that statement and let it fuel me to be one of the best on ball defenders. My teammates , my coaches, my family knew how bad I wanted to defend this year and every year to come . 
I’m proud to have been selected to 2nd All Defense ... y’all know what I’m going after next ______

Name: Vadeeva, Maria
Caption:
I’d like to analyze some problems of young athletes__
Today’s topic is stress and anxiety on games. I get a lot of DM’s about it and realize this is a major problem__

Being nervous is normal, both young, and professional athletes experience it. Stress appears out of fear of making a mistake, but, in fact, EVERYONE makes mistakes_
When you go out on the court, the main thing is to understand that even if you make a mistake and don’t do what you had to do, it’s not the end of the world.

Even the most famous athletes make mistakes, and it is normal! As soon as you let go of yourself and start enjoying the game, the anxiety will go away.
Trust me, you can do anything_

Tell me, what else bothers you?

Name: Wiese, Sydney
Caption:
I wasn’t going to accept this challenge. But then, I learned the intentions behind it. There are innocent women being killed in Turkey, “honor killings”. Women being murdered for bringing “dishonor” to their families, religion, communities. When a woman is killed, their picture is in the newspaper the next day- a black and white photo. 
 
The second picture is Pinar Gültekin, a 27 year old Turkish women who recently lost her life at the hands of a premeditated murderer. Her death has sparked urgency; urgency toward the Turkish government to protect women and prevent the government from taking away protections against domestic violence and cruel, abusive acts toward women. Her death has been the final straw for Turkish women’s rights activists, and hopefully for all of us. 
 
This challenge is a protest. It is standing with these innocent Turkish women. It is showing united urgency to make sure no more women/people are unjustifiably harmed/killed ever again. Women empower women, human beings empower human bei#ngs, always._#ChallengeAccepted_#Together

Name: Wiese, Sydney
Caption: Let me take a moment from where I sit. This is the place I would be before school, after school, before games, during football games, on weekends, with others, alone. I returned here whenever I was home from college. I have returned here after each pro season. In between overseas and the W- I return. I have leaned against this wall for years- dreaming of the moments I am living in. I have cried in here. Thrown the ball across the gym in frustration. Listened to countless Jbiebs albums. I have been built in here. There’s something special about the journey always leading you back to where you have come from- a moment of gratitude, a chance to look back to see how far you have traveled. A place that grounds me and fills me, reminding me we are really out here living what that young Swiese worked for. Allow me to take a moment to recognize her because she deserves that. And let me praise God for the path only He could carve out because He deserves that more. #ThanksForReadingMyMondayNovel #PeaceAndLerv

Name: Wiese, Sydney
Caption:
August 14th, 2014. Michelle Cusseaux. 50 years old. Killed in her own home by the Phoenix police when they were called for a mental health wellness check. Her mother, “Momma Fran” is known as the godmother of the Say Her Name movement. She brought her daughter’s casket to city hall in downtown Phoenix because she refused to let her daughter die in vain. She made sure Michelle’s name was HEARD- and we are listening. And we, too, are saying her name: MICHELLE CUSSEAUX. 
 
Join us and _@AAPolicyForum_in honoring Michelle and supporting the fight for justice: _https://aapf.org/sayhername
